{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/background-information/causes-risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"7317d644-d2ef-5ab1-8752-8210b1dd55aa","slug":"causes-risk-factors","fullItemName":"Causes and risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 28d58fd9-81b2-420e-bfdb-2ed7a69c6c31 --><h2>What are the causes and risk factors?</h2><!-- end field 28d58fd9-81b2-420e-bfdb-2ed7a69c6c31 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 0b725f4b-af3b-44f7-825a-f3212de062ad --><!-- begin field 69a83e05-224c-442f-97a2-95f55acc322f --><ul><li><strong>Venous skin changes are caused by sustained venous hypertension, which results from chronic venous insufficiency due to venous valve incompetence or an impaired calf muscle pump.</strong><ul><li>In the normal venous system, venous pressure decreases with exercise as a result of the action of the calf muscle pump. When the calf muscles relax, the valves in the perforating veins (which connect the superficial veins to the deep veins) prevent reflux of blood and the pressure remains low.</li><li>If there is reflux of blood due to valve damage or calf muscle pump impairment, the venous pressure remains high, resulting in venous distension, oedema, and venous skin changes (hyperpigmentation, venous eczema, lipodermatosclerosis, and <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/diagnosis/assessment/\">atrophie blanche</a>). As the condition of the skin and subcutaneous tissue worsens, it becomes increasingly vulnerable to ulceration. See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/leg-ulcer-venous/\">Leg ulcer - venous</a> for more information.</li><li>The exact cause of the skin changes is unclear. One theory is that it is due to leakage of blood constituents into the surrounding tissues, with subsequent activation of inflammatory cells and fibroblasts.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Risk factors include:</strong><ul><li>Advancing age.</li><li>Being overweight or obese.</li><li>Immobility.</li><li>Chronic swelling of lower leg, aggravated by hot weather and prolonged standing.</li><li>Varicose veins.</li><li>Previous history of deep vein thrombosis, cellulitis, or venous leg ulcers.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Grey et al, 2006</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Smith, 2006</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Barron et al, 2007</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Middleton, 2007</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Charles, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Kelechi, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">BAD, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">DermNet NZ, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Nazarko, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/venous-eczema-lipodermatosclerosis/references/\">Sundaresan, 2017</a>]</p><!-- end field 69a83e05-224c-442f-97a2-95f55acc322f --><!-- end item 0b725f4b-af3b-44f7-825a-f3212de062ad -->","topic":{"id":"a90d58ca-80ba-5e1b-aee1-810e3e75187f","topicId":"ea8f06ec-40eb-41f8-9dfd-55c794f27eef","top